  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework named \u2018Knowledge-Grounded AMR Refinement for Biomedical Event Understanding\u2019 (KG-AMR), which introduces a bidirectional interaction between Abstract Meaning Representations (AMRs) and external biomedical knowledge graphs (KGs) such as UMLS, SemMedDB, and Hetionet. Unlike existing approaches that use KGs only to enrich post-parsed representations, KG-AMR incorporates KG-derived biological plausibility into the AMR parsing process itself, forming a closed-loop refinement system. The core innovation lies in a dual-phase architecture: (1) a \u2018Forward Parsing\u2019 stage generates an initial AMR from biomedical text using a fine-tuned AMR parser (e.g., CAMR or NeuralAMR), followed by entity normalization to UMLS CUIs; and (2) a \u2018Backward Refinement\u2019 stage that evaluates the semantic coherence of each proposition in the AMR by aligning it with plausible paths in the biomedical KG using a cross-modal Graph Optimal Transport (GOT) scorer regularized with Deep Graph Infomax (DGI) to preserve global structure. Propositions with low alignment scores are flagged and re-parsed using a constrained decoding mechanism that biases syntactic choices toward biologically attested relations (e.g., favoring \u2018gene regulates disease\u2019 over \u2018disease regulates gene\u2019). This iterative refinement continues until convergence or a maximum iteration limit. The refined AMR is then fused with the matched KG subgraph via a Gated Heterogeneous Graph Neural Network (GH-GNN), where node updates are conditioned on both AMR semantic roles and KG relation types. A final counterfactual consistency module evaluates whether perturbing high-confidence KG edges induces logical contradictions in the AMR structure, further filtering spurious parses. This enables not only improved event extraction but also zero-shot generalization to novel entities by leveraging KG topology. We evaluate KG-AMR on BioNLP GENIA Event Extraction tasks and introduce a new diagnostic benchmark, BioCoherence, which measures the biological plausibility of AMR propositions through expert annotations of directional validity and mechanistic feasibility. By grounding semantic parsing in domain knowledge, KG-AMR shifts the paradigm from \u2018parse-then-enrich\u2019 to \u2018parse-with-knowledge\u2019, significantly improving the accuracy and interpretability of biomedical event understanding.",
