  "Idea": "The proposed idea centers on developing a novel framework called \u2018Knowledge-Enhanced AMR Reasoning for Biomedical Events\u2019 (KAR-Bio), which dynamically integrates Abstract Meaning Representations (AMRs) derived from biomedical text with external biomedical knowledge graphs (e.g., UMLS, Hetionet, or SemMedDB) to improve both the identification of complex biomedical events and the inference of underlying causal mechanisms. Unlike prior work that uses KGs to enrich token or entity embeddings within sequence models, KAR-Bio treats AMR as a structural query interface to retrieve semantically aligned subgraphs from the KG. Specifically, each AMR\u2014which captures propositional semantics such as \u2018Protein A activates Pathway B leading to Disease C\u2019\u2014is decomposed into predicate-argument triples. These are then matched against plausible paths in the biomedical KG using a cross-modal graph alignment model based on Graph Optimal Transport (GOT) and mutual information regularization. Once aligned, the fused AMR-KG graph undergoes a message-passing process where node representations are updated through a Gated Graph Neural Network conditioned on both syntactic roles (from AMR) and biological relation types (from KG). Crucially, we introduce a counterfactual intervention module that perturbs edges in the aligned graph to assess causal plausibility: if removing a \u2018activation\u2019 edge between two proteins significantly alters the predicted event outcome, it suggests a stronger causal role. This enables not only improved event classification but also explainable causal ranking of relationships. The system will be evaluated on BioNLP shared tasks (e.g., GENIA Event Extraction) and extended to a new benchmark we propose: CausalBioEvents, which annotates event sentences with expert-labeled mechanistic pathways and counterfactual feasibility scores. By bridging shallow event extraction with deep causal reasoning, KAR-Bio advances biomedical NLP