Both Idea 0 and Idea 1 propose highly novel integrations of Abstract Meaning Representations (AMRs) with biomedical knowledge graphs (KGs), leveraging advanced techniques such as Graph Optimal Transport (GOT), Deep Graph Infomax (DGI), and Gated Graph Neural Networks. However, when comparing against the provided related work, novelty must be assessed in context.

Paper 1 introduces an AMR-guided framework for joint information extraction, using AMR structures to guide message passing and decoding in IE tasks—this overlaps partially with the use of AMR as a structural scaffold but does not involve external KG integration during parsing or reasoning. Papers 3 and 4 explore LLM-KG integration via retrieval and alignment, but do not use AMR at all. Paper 5 discusses complex evidence reasoning in KGs using Bayesian methods, which is conceptually relevant to causal inference but operates in a different modeling space and does not involve AMR or event extraction. None of the papers integrate AMR parsing with dynamic KG alignment during semantic structure refinement or use counterfactual interventions over fused AMR-KG graphs for causal assessment.

